            },
            {
              "name": "Hip Flexor Stretch (90/90)",
              "reps_or_duration": "90 seconds each side",
              "notes": "Static hip opener"
            },
            {
              "name": "Foam Roll \u2014 Quads",
              "reps_or_duration": "2 minutes",
              "notes": "Reduce muscle tension post-workout"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      "rationale": {
        "session_why": {
          "text": "This session targets the oxidative energy system through sustained moderate-intensity work across three monostructural modalities. The 15-minute AMRAP keeps effort in the aerobic-dominant zone (>3-4 minutes per movement cycle), developing cardiovascular endurance and stamina. The strength block uses interval rows to build pacing discipline and aerobic power.",
          "source": "Gastin 2001 - Energy System Interaction",
          "url_or_ref": "Sports Medicine 31(10)"
        },
        "movement_why": {
          "text": "Monostructural movements (row, bike, jump rope) were selected to develop cardiovascular endurance without the technical complexity of barbell or gymnastics movements. This allows the athlete to focus purely on pacing and aerobic capacity. Rotating between three modalities prevents local muscular fatigue while maintaining cardiovascular demand.",
          "source": "Glassman 2002 - CrossFit Journal",
          "url_or_ref": "What is Fitness?"
        },
        "loading_why": {
          "text": "The interval rows in the strength block use 90-second rest to partially recover the phosphocreatine system while keeping the aerobic system engaged. The AMRAP uses bodyweight-only monostructural work to ensure intensity stays in the aerobic zone (70-75% max effort) rather than spiking into glycolytic overdrive. This polarized approach dedicates 80% of aerobic volume to low-moderate intensity.",
          "source": "Haff & Triplett - NSCA Essentials 4th ed",
          "url_or_ref": "Chapter 3: Energy Systems"
        }
      }
    },
