      "rationale": {
        "session_why": {
          "text": "This session combines monostructural cardio (rowing) with mixed-modal functional movements (kettlebell swings, pull-ups) to develop stamina \u2014 the ability to process, deliver, store, and utilize energy across different movement domains. The 12-15 minute time domain targets the oxidative system while maintaining moderate glycolytic contribution.",
          "source": "Glassman 2002 - CrossFit Journal",
          "url_or_ref": "What is Fitness? \u2014 10 Physical Skills"
        },
        "movement_why": {
          "text": "The kettlebell swing provides a posterior chain hinge pattern under cardiovascular stress. Pull-ups add an upper body pulling component, creating full-body muscular endurance demand. Rowing intervals maintain aerobic base while the swing and pull-up create brief glycolytic spikes. This mixed-modal approach develops GPP \u2014 general physical preparedness across time domains and movement patterns.",
          "source": "CrossFit Level 2 Training Guide",
          "url_or_ref": "2022 edition"
        },
        "loading_why": {
          "text": "The strength block uses 60-second rest intervals to develop strength-endurance rather than maximal strength. Five sets of 20 swings builds work capacity in the hinge pattern. The metcon uses moderate loading (24kg/16kg) and time cap of 18 minutes to keep intensity sustainable \u2014 this prevents excessive glycolytic buildup and keeps the athlete in the aerobic-dominant zone for the majority of the workout.",
          "source": "Haff & Triplett - NSCA Essentials 4th ed",
          "url_or_ref": "Chapter 3: Energy System Interaction"
        }
      }
