      "rationale": {
        "session_why": {
          "text": "This running-focused session develops cardiovascular endurance and stamina through sustained aerobic work. The 800m intervals in the strength block target aerobic threshold \u2014 the upper limit of purely oxidative metabolism. The For Time metcon combines running with bodyweight movements to develop the ability to maintain output under cumulative fatigue across 15-18 minutes (oxidative system dominant).",
          "source": "Gastin 2001 - Energy System Interaction",
          "url_or_ref": "Sports Medicine 31(10): oxidative system dominant beyond 3-4 minutes"
        },
        "movement_why": {
          "text": "Running is a foundational monostructural movement that develops cardiovascular endurance without equipment. Air squats and burpees add functional movement patterns under cardiovascular stress, training the ability to maintain motor control and power output when the oxidative system is taxed. This session balances pure aerobic development (running) with mixed-modal GPP (air squats, burpees).",
          "source": "Glassman 2002 - CrossFit Journal",
          "url_or_ref": "What is Fitness? \u2014 GPP across broad time and modal domains"
        },
        "loading_why": {
          "text": "The 800m intervals use 2-minute rest to allow partial recovery while keeping the aerobic system engaged \u2014 this is threshold training. The For Time metcon uses bodyweight-only movements at a pace sustainable across 3 rounds, preventing excessive glycolytic buildup. The 18-minute time cap ensures the workout remains in the oxidative-dominant zone rather than becoming a glycolytic sprint.",
          "source": "Haff & Triplett - NSCA Essentials 4th ed",
          "url_or_ref": "Chapter 3: Energy Systems \u2014 oxidative dominance >10 minutes"
        }
      }
